1
01:00:00,000 --> 01:00:03,833
<b>Since 2021, Africa has experienced 13</b>

2
01:00:03,833 --> 01:00:06,066
<b>military coups and coup attempts.</b>

3
01:00:06,699 --> 01:00:09,400
<b>All but one happened in the Sahel in West</b>

4
01:00:09,400 --> 01:00:11,000
<b>Africa, predominantly</b>

5
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:12,599
<b>former French colonies.</b>

6
01:00:13,233 --> 01:00:15,699
<b>That concentration demands explanation.</b>

7
01:00:16,733 --> 01:00:19,166
<b>Most global terrorism no longer centers</b>

8
01:00:19,166 --> 01:00:20,766
<b>in Afghanistan or Iraq.</b>

9
01:00:21,599 --> 01:00:23,133
<b>It's concentrated in</b>

10
01:00:23,133 --> 01:00:24,633
<b>Africa's Sahel region.</b>

11
01:00:25,233 --> 01:00:27,933
<b>Mali, Niger, Burkina Faso.</b>

12
01:00:28,033 --> 01:00:29,133
<b>The same countries</b>

13
01:00:29,133 --> 01:00:31,233
<b>experiencing this coup wave.</b>

14
01:00:31,766 --> 01:00:33,766
<b>Political scientists have started calling</b>

15
01:00:33,766 --> 01:00:35,833
<b>these events coupvolutions.</b>

16
01:00:36,366 --> 01:00:38,533
<b>Coups driven by popular protests rather</b>

17
01:00:38,533 --> 01:00:40,033
<b>than elite power struggles.</b>

18
01:00:40,633 --> 01:00:42,800
<b>Today I'm examining three myths that</b>

19
01:00:42,800 --> 01:00:43,733
<b>obscure what's</b>

20
01:00:43,733 --> 01:00:45,300
<b>actually driving this crisis.</b>

21
01:00:45,900 --> 01:00:47,133
<b>Not to pick sides, but</b>

22
01:00:47,133 --> 01:00:48,866
<b>to understand the pattern.</b>

23
01:00:49,533 --> 01:00:50,833
<b>Here's the standard narrative.</b>

24
01:00:51,466 --> 01:00:52,533
<b>French colonial rule,</b>

25
01:00:52,966 --> 01:00:54,033
<b>despite its problems,</b>

26
01:00:54,233 --> 01:00:56,400
<b>built infrastructure and institutions</b>

27
01:00:56,400 --> 01:00:58,366
<b>that benefited African development.</b>

28
01:00:59,266 --> 01:01:01,633
<b>France's continued involvement maintains</b>

29
01:01:01,633 --> 01:01:03,233
<b>that constructive relationship.</b>

30
01:01:03,666 --> 01:01:06,166
<b>Let me show you what happened when one</b>

31
01:01:06,166 --> 01:01:07,866
<b>country tested that narrative.</b>

32
01:01:08,366 --> 01:01:11,800
<b>In 1958, French colonies faced a choice.</b>

33
01:01:12,333 --> 01:01:15,099
<b>Join the new French community or vote for</b>

34
01:01:15,099 --> 01:01:16,233
<b>immediate independence.</b>

35
01:01:16,933 --> 01:01:20,733
<b>Only Guinea under Sékou Touré voted no.</b>

36
01:01:21,366 --> 01:01:23,233
<b>France's response was immediate.</b>

37
01:01:23,566 --> 01:01:25,500
<b>They withdrew military support,</b>

38
01:01:26,366 --> 01:01:28,133
<b>administrative staff, infrastructure,</b>

39
01:01:28,933 --> 01:01:29,866
<b>telephones, light</b>

40
01:01:29,866 --> 01:01:31,099
<b>bulbs, medical supplies.</b>

41
01:01:31,833 --> 01:01:33,766
<b>But declassified documents reveal</b>

42
01:01:33,766 --> 01:01:35,333
<b>something more calculated.</b>

43
01:01:35,933 --> 01:01:36,866
<b>French intelligence</b>

44
01:01:36,866 --> 01:01:38,633
<b>launched Operation Persil.</b>

45
01:01:39,133 --> 01:01:40,066
<b>They used government</b>

46
01:01:40,066 --> 01:01:42,300
<b>printing presses to mass produce</b>

47
01:01:42,633 --> 01:01:45,266
<b>counterfeit Guinean currency and flood</b>

48
01:01:45,266 --> 01:01:47,833
<b>Guinea's economy with fake money.</b>

49
01:01:48,466 --> 01:01:50,566
<b>Maurice Robert, who directed this</b>

50
01:01:50,566 --> 01:01:52,633
<b>operation, later described it.</b>

51
01:01:52,633 --> 01:01:54,566
<b>The operation was a total success.</b>

52
01:01:55,333 --> 01:01:57,366
<b>Guinea's economy, already very weak,</b>

53
01:01:57,866 --> 01:01:59,066
<b>never fully recovered.</b>

54
01:01:59,900 --> 01:02:02,433
<b>Now, Robert claimed this wasn't</b>

55
01:02:02,433 --> 01:02:03,166
<b>punishment for</b>

56
01:02:03,166 --> 01:02:04,766
<b>Guinea's independence vote.</b>

57
01:02:05,133 --> 01:02:06,966
<b>He said it was necessary Cold War</b>

58
01:02:06,966 --> 01:02:09,599
<b>strategy, preventing the Soviet bloc,</b>

59
01:02:09,800 --> 01:02:11,366
<b>which was interested in</b>

60
01:02:11,366 --> 01:02:13,166
<b>Guinea's mineral resources,</b>

61
01:02:13,166 --> 01:02:15,166
<b>from gaining a bridgehead</b>

62
01:02:15,166 --> 01:02:16,800
<b>for the spread of subversion.</b>

63
01:02:17,233 --> 01:02:18,733
<b>But here's what matters.</b>

64
01:02:18,966 --> 01:02:21,566
<b>Whatever the stated motive, the effect</b>

65
01:02:21,566 --> 01:02:22,699
<b>was economic collapse.</b>

66
01:02:23,199 --> 01:02:25,733
<b>Currency depreciation, soaring prices.</b>

67
01:02:26,033 --> 01:02:28,466
<b>And French Prime Minister Georges</b>

68
01:02:28,466 --> 01:02:29,766
<b>Pompidou used Guinea</b>

69
01:02:29,766 --> 01:02:31,566
<b>as an explicit warning</b>

70
01:02:31,566 --> 01:02:33,866
<b>to other African countries considering</b>

71
01:02:33,866 --> 01:02:36,433
<b>leaving the French monetary system.</b>

72
01:02:36,833 --> 01:02:38,133
<b>Let the experience of</b>

73
01:02:38,133 --> 01:02:40,133
<b>Sékou Touré take its course.</b>

74
01:02:40,733 --> 01:02:43,466
<b>Many Africans are beginning to realize</b>

75
01:02:43,466 --> 01:02:46,233
<b>that Guinea's policy is suicidal</b>

76
01:02:46,866 --> 01:02:49,833
<b>and contrary to the interests of Africa.</b>

77
01:02:50,266 --> 01:02:51,766
<b>That brings us to the system that</b>

78
01:02:51,766 --> 01:02:54,066
<b>replaced direct colonial control.</b>

79
01:02:54,633 --> 01:02:55,633
<b>The CFA franc.</b>

80
01:02:56,266 --> 01:02:57,699
<b>14 African countries</b>

81
01:02:57,699 --> 01:02:59,699
<b>still use this currency today.</b>

82
01:03:00,233 --> 01:03:01,900
<b>Communauté Financière Africaine.</b>

83
01:03:02,566 --> 01:03:04,266
<b>African financial community.</b>

84
01:03:04,933 --> 01:03:07,366
<b>These countries must deposit substantial</b>

85
01:03:07,366 --> 01:03:08,533
<b>portions of their</b>

86
01:03:08,533 --> 01:03:10,000
<b>foreign exchange reserves</b>

87
01:03:10,066 --> 01:03:12,866
<b>with the French treasury, a requirement</b>

88
01:03:12,866 --> 01:03:14,466
<b>that continues for</b>

89
01:03:14,466 --> 01:03:16,266
<b>central African nations.</b>

90
01:03:17,500 --> 01:03:19,766
<b>France effectively controls monetary</b>

91
01:03:19,766 --> 01:03:21,733
<b>policy for these countries,</b>

92
01:03:22,300 --> 01:03:24,366
<b>setting interest rates, managing</b>

93
01:03:24,366 --> 01:03:27,033
<b>reserves, maintaining fixed exchange</b>

94
01:03:27,033 --> 01:03:28,266
<b>rates with the euro.</b>

95
01:03:28,966 --> 01:03:30,833
<b>Now, the system has defenders.</b>

96
01:03:31,800 --> 01:03:33,866
<b>President Alassane Ouattara of Cote</b>

97
01:03:33,866 --> 01:03:35,466
<b>d'Ivoire, former governor</b>

98
01:03:35,466 --> 01:03:37,333
<b>of the regional central bank,</b>

99
01:03:37,966 --> 01:03:41,833
<b>argues CFA countries are better off than</b>

100
01:03:41,833 --> 01:03:43,033
<b>Anglophone countries</b>

101
01:03:43,033 --> 01:03:44,433
<b>because of this stability.</b>

102
01:03:45,066 --> 01:03:47,133
<b>He points to inflation rates.</b>

103
01:03:47,533 --> 01:03:50,733
<b>Cote d'Ivoire averaged 6% inflation</b>

104
01:03:50,733 --> 01:03:53,133
<b>compared to Ghana's 29%.</b>

105
01:03:54,733 --> 01:03:57,966
<b>Ouattara claims the CFA franc has</b>

106
01:03:57,966 --> 01:03:59,733
<b>fostered the most</b>

107
01:03:59,733 --> 01:04:02,199
<b>continuous growth in the long term.</b>

108
01:04:02,966 --> 01:04:04,633
<b>French officials echo this.</b>

109
01:04:05,366 --> 01:04:08,766
<b>Economic minister Michel Sappin described</b>

110
01:04:08,766 --> 01:04:10,333
<b>the arrangement as</b>

111
01:04:10,333 --> 01:04:12,400
<b>France acting in a completely</b>

112
01:04:12,466 --> 01:04:14,933
<b>disinterested manner out of pure</b>

113
01:04:14,933 --> 01:04:18,033
<b>friendship, guaranteeing unlimited</b>

114
01:04:18,033 --> 01:04:19,733
<b>convertibility to prevent</b>

115
01:04:19,733 --> 01:04:20,800
<b>currency collapse.</b>

116
01:04:22,000 --> 01:04:24,466
<b>But critics, including a growing number</b>

117
01:04:24,466 --> 01:04:25,833
<b>of African economists,</b>

118
01:04:26,666 --> 01:04:27,966
<b>argue those benefits</b>

119
01:04:27,966 --> 01:04:30,166
<b>mask structural problems.</b>

120
01:04:30,633 --> 01:04:33,133
<b>The fixed exchange rate creates what they</b>

121
01:04:33,133 --> 01:04:35,033
<b>call low competitiveness.</b>

122
01:04:35,800 --> 01:04:38,566
<b>It makes African exports more expensive</b>

123
01:04:38,566 --> 01:04:40,900
<b>while making imports from Europe cheaper.</b>

124
01:04:41,266 --> 01:04:42,733
<b>That undermines local</b>

125
01:04:42,733 --> 01:04:44,533
<b>manufacturing and agriculture.</b>

126
01:04:45,133 --> 01:04:47,133
<b>And the resource extraction patterns</b>

127
01:04:47,133 --> 01:04:48,833
<b>reveal whose interests</b>

128
01:04:48,833 --> 01:04:50,833
<b>the system prioritizes.</b>

129
01:04:51,266 --> 01:04:53,933
<b>Niger's uranium, for example, provides</b>

130
01:04:53,933 --> 01:04:55,533
<b>significant fuel for</b>

131
01:04:55,533 --> 01:04:57,466
<b>France's nuclear reactors,</b>

132
01:04:57,966 --> 01:05:00,500
<b>which generates 75% of</b>

133
01:05:00,500 --> 01:05:01,666
<b>France's electricity.</b>

134
01:05:02,133 --> 01:05:04,933
<b>Yet Niger's royalties remain notably</b>

135
01:05:04,933 --> 01:05:07,633
<b>lower than what the same French companies</b>

136
01:05:07,633 --> 01:05:10,400
<b>pay in other uranium-producing countries.</b>

137
01:05:10,966 --> 01:05:15,366
<b>A 2019 Afrobarometer poll found that</b>

138
01:05:15,366 --> 01:05:18,433
<b>Togolese citizens were overwhelmingly in</b>

139
01:05:18,433 --> 01:05:20,599
<b>favor of leaving the CFA franc,</b>

140
01:05:21,133 --> 01:05:23,800
<b>reflecting a widespread belief that the</b>

141
01:05:23,800 --> 01:05:25,166
<b>currency primarily</b>

142
01:05:25,166 --> 01:05:27,233
<b>serves French interests</b>

143
01:05:27,666 --> 01:05:29,433
<b>rather than African development.</b>

144
01:05:29,833 --> 01:05:31,566
<b>So the question isn't whether the CFA</b>

145
01:05:31,566 --> 01:05:33,733
<b>franc provides some stability.</b>

146
01:05:34,533 --> 01:05:34,933
<b>It does.</b>

147
01:05:35,533 --> 01:05:36,733
<b>But the question is</b>

148
01:05:36,733 --> 01:05:39,599
<b>stability for whom and at what cost?</b>

149
01:05:40,099 --> 01:05:42,366
<b>The second myth, French military</b>

150
01:05:42,366 --> 01:05:45,066
<b>operations in Mali serve as</b>

151
01:05:45,066 --> 01:05:46,833
<b>necessary stabilizing forces,</b>

152
01:05:47,099 --> 01:05:48,199
<b>preventing terrorist</b>

153
01:05:48,199 --> 01:05:50,333
<b>expansion and state collapse.</b>

154
01:05:51,266 --> 01:05:52,566
<b>Let's examine the evidence.</b>

155
01:05:53,233 --> 01:05:56,533
<b>In 2013, armed groups seized</b>

156
01:05:56,533 --> 01:05:58,433
<b>towns across northern Mali.</b>

157
01:05:59,199 --> 01:06:01,233
<b>France deployed Operation Serval.</b>

158
01:06:01,966 --> 01:06:05,233
<b>5,000 troops, air support, advanced</b>

159
01:06:05,233 --> 01:06:06,199
<b>military technology.</b>

160
01:06:07,199 --> 01:06:07,966
<b>The mission?</b>

161
01:06:08,533 --> 01:06:09,533
<b>Eliminate terrorist</b>

162
01:06:09,533 --> 01:06:11,533
<b>threats and restore stability.</b>

163
01:06:11,966 --> 01:06:14,599
<b>A decade later, Mali's prime minister</b>

164
01:06:14,599 --> 01:06:16,066
<b>described the outcome.</b>

165
01:06:16,566 --> 01:06:18,666
<b>Hundreds and hundreds of Malians have</b>

166
01:06:18,666 --> 01:06:20,466
<b>been massacred over the years,</b>

167
01:06:20,699 --> 01:06:21,866
<b>despite the presence</b>

168
01:06:21,866 --> 01:06:23,866
<b>of over 50,000 soldiers.</b>

169
01:06:24,466 --> 01:06:27,866
<b>By 2021, the region experienced over</b>

170
01:06:27,866 --> 01:06:30,599
<b>2,500 violent incidents</b>

171
01:06:30,599 --> 01:06:32,733
<b>and nearly 6,000 deaths.</b>

172
01:06:33,133 --> 01:06:34,666
<b>Violence didn't just continue.</b>

173
01:06:35,066 --> 01:06:37,866
<b>It spread from Mali into Niger and</b>

174
01:06:37,866 --> 01:06:39,199
<b>Burkina Faso during</b>

175
01:06:39,199 --> 01:06:40,833
<b>French military deployment.</b>

176
01:06:41,866 --> 01:06:43,533
<b>Academic analysis concludes</b>

177
01:06:43,533 --> 01:06:45,766
<b>the strategy was doomed to fail</b>

178
01:06:46,066 --> 01:06:48,599
<b>because it prioritized killing militants</b>

179
01:06:48,599 --> 01:06:49,966
<b>over addressing why</b>

180
01:06:49,966 --> 01:06:51,766
<b>people join militant groups in</b>

181
01:06:51,766 --> 01:06:52,699
<b>the first place.</b>

182
01:06:53,133 --> 01:06:54,233
<b>Economic inequality,</b>

183
01:06:54,766 --> 01:06:57,266
<b>governance failures, ethnic grievances,</b>

184
01:06:58,366 --> 01:06:59,033
<b>French tactical</b>

185
01:06:59,033 --> 01:07:00,866
<b>decisions made this worse.</b>

186
01:07:01,433 --> 01:07:04,633
<b>To fight terrorist groups, French forces</b>

187
01:07:04,633 --> 01:07:06,566
<b>collaborated with local militias.</b>

188
01:07:07,500 --> 01:07:09,333
<b>Some committed atrocities against</b>

189
01:07:09,333 --> 01:07:10,733
<b>civilian communities.</b>

190
01:07:11,533 --> 01:07:14,133
<b>That drove civilians to join armed groups</b>

191
01:07:14,133 --> 01:07:15,800
<b>for protection from the</b>

192
01:07:15,800 --> 01:07:18,033
<b>very militias France supported.</b>

193
01:07:18,533 --> 01:07:21,033
<b>Even French analysts recognized this.</b>

194
01:07:21,466 --> 01:07:23,466
<b>Internal assessments noted that</b>

195
01:07:23,466 --> 01:07:25,066
<b>unilateral interventions</b>

196
01:07:25,766 --> 01:07:28,533
<b>fuel anti-French sentiment, undermining</b>

197
01:07:28,533 --> 01:07:30,333
<b>France's regional influence.</b>

198
01:07:31,300 --> 01:07:34,233
<b>So if French presence provided stability,</b>

199
01:07:34,733 --> 01:07:37,000
<b>why did violence increase and spread?</b>

200
01:07:37,833 --> 01:07:40,099
<b>And why did Mali's democratic government</b>

201
01:07:40,099 --> 01:07:42,033
<b>collapse under military rule</b>

202
01:07:42,233 --> 01:07:44,633
<b>while French forces remained deployed?</b>

203
01:07:44,933 --> 01:07:47,233
<b>The evidence suggests the intervention</b>

204
01:07:47,233 --> 01:07:49,133
<b>created conditions for the</b>

205
01:07:49,133 --> 01:07:51,199
<b>instability it claimed to prevent.</b>

206
01:07:51,833 --> 01:07:54,066
<b>Standard analysis treats each military</b>

207
01:07:54,066 --> 01:07:56,966
<b>takeover as isolated domestic failure.</b>

208
01:07:57,533 --> 01:07:58,833
<b>Corrupt officials, weak</b>

209
01:07:58,833 --> 01:08:00,833
<b>institutions, poor leadership.</b>

210
01:08:01,666 --> 01:08:02,866
<b>But watch the pattern.</b>

211
01:08:03,966 --> 01:08:05,166
<b>Mali terminated defense</b>

212
01:08:05,166 --> 01:08:06,466
<b>agreements with France,</b>

213
01:08:07,166 --> 01:08:10,166
<b>expelled the French ambassador, demanded</b>

214
01:08:10,166 --> 01:08:12,033
<b>withdrawal of French troops.</b>

215
01:08:13,133 --> 01:08:14,833
<b>Burkina Faso did the same.</b>

216
01:08:15,466 --> 01:08:16,166
<b>Then Niger.</b>

217
01:08:16,933 --> 01:08:19,666
<b>All three suspended economic agreements</b>

218
01:08:19,666 --> 01:08:21,366
<b>with Paris and shifted</b>

219
01:08:21,366 --> 01:08:24,133
<b>towards Russia, Turkey or China.</b>

220
01:08:24,466 --> 01:08:26,966
<b>That's not three isolated events.</b>

221
01:08:27,433 --> 01:08:28,566
<b>That's coordination.</b>

222
01:08:29,033 --> 01:08:31,100
<b>The military leaders explicitly used</b>

223
01:08:31,100 --> 01:08:32,433
<b>anti-French sentiment</b>

224
01:08:32,566 --> 01:08:34,633
<b>to justify their takeovers</b>

225
01:08:34,633 --> 01:08:36,266
<b>and build popular support.</b>

226
01:08:36,733 --> 01:08:38,633
<b>Research on these crews identifies</b>

227
01:08:38,633 --> 01:08:39,966
<b>anti-French sentiment</b>

228
01:08:40,633 --> 01:08:43,866
<b>as the fundamental factor contributing to</b>

229
01:08:43,866 --> 01:08:45,600
<b>the recent spike in coup d'etat.</b>

230
01:08:46,266 --> 01:08:49,133
<b>Finding that one of the main triggers for</b>

231
01:08:49,133 --> 01:08:51,366
<b>opposition protests is</b>

232
01:08:51,366 --> 01:08:53,033
<b>French presence in the country.</b>

233
01:08:53,466 --> 01:08:55,800
<b>Now we need to be very clear about what</b>

234
01:08:55,800 --> 01:08:56,399
<b>these military</b>

235
01:08:56,399 --> 01:08:58,100
<b>governments have actually delivered.</b>

236
01:08:58,433 --> 01:09:00,633
<b>In Mali, the pivot towards cooperation</b>

237
01:09:00,633 --> 01:09:02,766
<b>with Russia's Wagner group has seen</b>

238
01:09:02,800 --> 01:09:05,199
<b>increased violence against civilians and</b>

239
01:09:05,199 --> 01:09:07,266
<b>little counterinsurgency impact.</b>

240
01:09:07,699 --> 01:09:10,399
<b>In Burkina Faso, the convolution raises a</b>

241
01:09:10,399 --> 01:09:11,533
<b>fundamental question.</b>

242
01:09:12,000 --> 01:09:15,100
<b>Security analysts note it remains unclear</b>

243
01:09:15,100 --> 01:09:17,266
<b>how, or if this can improve</b>

244
01:09:17,266 --> 01:09:18,933
